You are given a TypeScript module for a site-publishing service. Each `publish*` function writes rows to the database inside a transaction and then triggers an external build (an out-of-process side effect that reads the committed database state).

There is one invariant the module must uphold:
  • The external build (`triggerBuild`) must run ONLY AFTER its transaction has fully committed — never while a transaction is still open. If a build starts inside an open transaction it may read stale/uncommitted rows, and if the transaction later rolls back the build is orphaned.
  • Database writes (`writeRow`) must still happen INSIDE a transaction.

Several functions currently violate this. A violation may be direct, hidden behind a helper call, or buried inside a nested transaction. Some functions may already be correct. Audit EVERY publish function and fix every violation, without breaking the ones that are already correct.

Constraints:
  • Do NOT modify the provided runtime-primitives section (the marked block at the top).
  • Keep every existing named `export` and preserve each function's observable behaviour: it must still perform its database writes inside a committed transaction and still trigger exactly one build.

Here is the module:

```ts
// ─── Runtime primitives — PROVIDED. Do NOT modify anything in this section. ───
// They model a database transaction and an external build (an out-of-process side
// effect, e.g. kicking off a CI/CodeBuild job). The invariants they enforce:
//   • A build must NEVER start while a transaction is still open (triggerBuild throws).
//   • A row write must ALWAYS happen inside a transaction (writeRow throws otherwise).
let _depth = 0
export const _events: string[] = []
export function _reset(): void {
  _events.length = 0
  _depth = 0
}
export async function withTransaction<T>(fn: () => Promise<T>): Promise<T> {
  _depth++
  _events.push("txn:begin")
  try {
    return await fn()
  } finally {
    _depth--
    if (_depth === 0) _events.push("txn:commit")
  }
}
export function writeRow(table: string): void {
  if (_depth === 0) throw new Error(`writeRow('${table}') must run inside a transaction`)
  _events.push(`write:${table}`)
}
export function triggerBuild(siteId: string): void {
  if (_depth > 0) throw new Error(`build for '${siteId}' started while a transaction was still open`)
  _events.push(`build:${siteId}`)
}
// ─── End provided section. Refactor everything BELOW. ───

export async function publishConfig(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Site")
    triggerBuild(siteId)
  })
}

export async function publishTheme(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Theme")
    triggerBuild(siteId)
  })
}

export async function publishNavbar(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Navbar")
    triggerBuild(siteId)
  })
}

export async function publishFooter(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Footer")
    triggerBuild(siteId)
  })
}

// Publishes via a helper — the build is one call away from the transaction.
async function runPublish(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  triggerBuild(siteId)
}
export async function republish(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Site")
    await runPublish(siteId)
  })
}

// Writes an audit row in a nested transaction, then builds.
export async function publishWithAudit(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Site")
    await withTransaction(async () => {
      writeRow("AuditLog")
    })
    triggerBuild(siteId)
  })
}

// Already correct: the build runs after the transaction has committed.
export async function publishNotification(siteId: string): Promise<void> {
  await withTransaction(async () => {
    writeRow("Notification")
  })
  triggerBuild(siteId)
}
```

